You are right regarding Bow it takes only page content. Actually I had
a parser which takes the link, gets the page content and then feed it
to Bow. But it will be much more efficient to use to the file
downloaded by heritrix.

&gt;This new BowProcessor could be inserted into the Heritrix extractor
&gt;processing step before all other extractors.

this sounds like the best approach to me. Any pointers on how should I
write a processor and add it to Heritrix? I guess I should read
developers manual and brush up JAVA(I prefer C/perl). 

thanks for your valuable suggestions,

Saurabh




--- In archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com, stack &lt;stack@a...&gt; wrote:
&gt; It looks like Bow (http://www-2.cs.cmu.edu/~mccallum/bow/) wants to
look 
&gt; at content, not links.  Is that right?  Or is it that your classifier 
&gt; just looks at links?  If its looking at links only, then you&#39;d override 
&gt; the PostSelector, the processor that schedules links with the Frontier, 
&gt; so that you could do a JNI call out to Bow to ask it if a link
should be 
&gt; scheduled, or you could add a new Processor into the Post-Processing 
&gt; Chain
(http://crawler.archive.org/articles/developer_manual.html#N1012B) 
&gt; that happened before the PostSelector and in here knock out URLs you 
&gt; don&#39;t want crawled.   If you need to feed Bow the page content, you&#39;d 
&gt; write a new Processor that passed Bow via JNI the file on disk that had 
&gt; the downloaded document (We might need to do a little work in Heritrix 
&gt; because we usually keep the request in memory only spooling to disk if 
&gt; the request is &#39;large&#39;).    Bow would do its thing and return a score 
&gt; back across the JNI bridge.  Your BowProcessor would check the score 
&gt; against a configurable boundary.  This new BowProcessor could be 
&gt; inserted into the Heritrix extractor processing step before all other 
&gt; extractors.  If the returned value was above the boundary score, then 
&gt; you&#39;d let the page through to the extractors for links to be found; 
&gt; otherwise, you&#39;d skip the extractors so no URLs would be pulled from 
&gt; this page.  Or you&#39;d package your processor as a filter for the 
&gt; ARCWriter step and if the score was below the configured threshold, 
&gt; you&#39;d not write the page into the ARCs.
&gt; 
&gt; Maybe you&#39;d combinations of the above?
&gt; 
&gt; Let us know how we can help.  Integrating such a classifier would be a 
&gt; nice feather in Heritrix&#39;s cap.
&gt; 
&gt; St.Ack
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Saurabh Pathak wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; --- In archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com, stack &lt;stack@a...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; The focusing dials on Heritrix are in synopsis:
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; - Scope (Domain, Host, Path, etc.)
&gt; &gt; &gt; - Filters (Regex on URL, Regex on Content-Type, etc.).
&gt; &gt; &gt; - Size of response, time to complete response.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Sounds like you want a &#39;classification dial&#39; of some sort.  Can you
&gt; &gt; &gt; describe what this classifier would do?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Thanks for your reply Stack. I dont think scope or filter dials are
&gt; &gt; sufficient to meet my purpose.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Here is a brief description of what I want to do,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I want to build a crawl collection for a topic and hence I need to
&gt; &gt; run a focused crawl instead of a normal crawl. I have trained the Bow
&gt; &gt; classifier to recognize pages relevant to the topic. Now I want to
&gt; &gt; hook up this trained classifier to  Heritrix in such a manner that
&gt; &gt; Heritrix consults this classifer before following any link. In short I
&gt; &gt; want to add a URL to frontier only if it belongs to the topic (if the
&gt; &gt; score returned by the classifier meets a minimum threshold value) 
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Is there a way to accomplish above task?
&gt; &gt; please let me know if anything is still unclear or not properly
&gt; &gt; explained by me.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Best,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Saurabh
